default              
defaultPrimates are among the most intelligent animals; they are 
defaultsocially 
defaultcomplex
default, long lived and
default require specialist keeping
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default1.3
default              
defaultIt is understandable, therefore, that people should be concerned when they hear of primat
defaultes being kept in inappropriate conditions that contravene the Animal Welfare Act 2006.
default&#xa0;
default1.4
default              
defaultDefra’s
default responsibility is to ensure that animals are provided with the appropriate protection and that enforcers have the necessary powers to take action in order t
defaulto investigate allegations of cruelty or poor welfare.  Defra also sees its role as reminding 
defaultowners and 
defaultpotential owners of their responsibility to provide for the welfare needs of their animals, as required under the 
defaultA
defaultnimal Welfare Act 2006. 
default&#xa0;
default1.5
default              
defaultDefra w
defaultould like to make it clear that primates should not be kept as pets in the 
defaultconventional 
defaultmeaning of the word “pet”.  If keeping a primate as a pet means keeping it in the domestic setting
default,
default whether in a cage or running free, 
defaultthen this would be likely to be
default 
defaulti
defaultn breach of 
defaultsection 9 of 
defaultthe Animal Welfare Act 2006
default (the need to provide an animal with its welfare needs)
default.  However, keeping primates in a 
defaultsuitable social 
defaultgroup setting in suitably constructed accommodation and ensuring that 
defaultall of 
defaultthe welfare needs of the animals are met 
defaultsh
defaultould 
defaultcomply with the Animal Welfare Act requirements 
default- as long as all other related regulations are being met.
