default2.1
default              
defaultPeriodically the Government receives correspondence from interested stakeholders or ind
defaultividual members of the public, usually in response to campaigns from stakeholders, expressing their concern about the conditions in which some primates are being kept by individual owners.  Anecdotal evidence of solitary primates being kept in small cages 
defaultin a domestic setting and being fed inappropriate diets are central to most of the concerns.  Other concerns relate to the ease with which primates are advertised for sale on the internet.  Many adverts use terminology such as “good with children”, “diaper
default trained” and “will provide good company”.  Such claims are disturbing because
default we do not consider that
default primates should be kept in a domestic setting.
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default              
defaultThere are also allegations that many primates are being kept in breach of other legislation (e.g. the
default Convention on the 
defaultInternational 
defaultTrade in Endangered Species (CITES) as well as the Dangerous Wild Animals Act 1976
default - 
defaultsee “Legislative framework”
default.
default 
default Under the 1976 Act
default,
default anyone wishing to keep a listed animal must obtain a valid licence from their local auth
defaultority.  There are claims that listed animals are being kept without an appropriate licence.
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default              
defaultOther allegations claim that primates are taken from their natural habitat in the wild and transported to developed countries such as the UK and the US to be k
defaultept as pets.  Such action is likely to be in breach of laws in other countries as well as CITES and regulations on the welfare of animals in transport. However, there is little evidence to show that wild-caught primates are being transported to this countr
defaulty for the pet trade.  It is more likely that UK residents will obtain a captive bred primate than one that is wild caught and then transported to this country.
default&#xa0;
defaultAnimal Welfare Act 2006
default3.1
default              
defaultFor years, the Protection of Animals Act 1911
default was the principal piece of legislation that protected animals from acts of cruelty.  Under this law, it was an offence to cause any unnecessary suffering to an animal.  This stood the test of time and was used by agencies, such as the RSPCA to prosecute a
defaultround 800-1,000 people for animal cruelty each year.
default&#xa0;
default3.2
default              
defaultHowever, in 2007 the Animal Welfare Act 2006 (the “2006 Act”) came into force.  This largely replaced the 1911 Act and as well as retaining the “causing unnecessary suffering offence”
default,
default also introduc
defaulted the “welfare offence” under which an owner or keeper could be prosecuted for failing to provide for the welfare needs of 
defaultan 
defaultanimal.  The welfare offence was based on a similar offence that related to farm animals.  The new offence meant that for the fir
defaultst time owners of non-farm animals could be prosecuted for failing to look after their animals properly, even if no suffering had actually occurred.  This ha
defaults
default the benefit of not having to wait for an animal to undergo suffering before action c
defaultan
default be taken.  
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default              
defaultUnder the 2006 Act, the maximum penalty for causing unnecessary suffering to an animal is 6 months imprisonment or a fine of £20,000, or both.
default 
defaultThe maximum penalty for failing to provide for the welfare needs of an animal is 6 months impri
defaultsonment or a fine of £5,000, or both.
default&#xa0;
default3.4
default              
defaultT
defaulthe welfare of primates is 
defaulttherefore 
defaultprotected 
defaultunder the 2006 Act
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultPrimate 
defaultCode of Practice
default3.5
default              
defaultIn addition, under the 2006 Act
default there are powers for the Secretary of State to make statutory codes of practice for
default the welfare of animals or animal related activities.  In 2010, Defra introduced the 
defaultCode of Practice for the Welfare of Privately Kept Non-human Primates
default.  The code was made in response to 
defaultconcerns about primates expressed during the passage of the Animal
default Welfare Bill through Parliament.  
default&#xa0;
default3.6
default              
defaultWhilst it is not a
default specific o
defaultffence to breach the 
defaultC
defaultode, if proceedings 
defaultare brought under the Act, the Court can take into account
default 
defaultthe extent to which 
defaultsomeone
default ha
defaults
default complied, or failed
default 
defaultto comply, with the Code in decid
defaulting whether 
defaultthe
defaulty
default 
defaulthave committed an offence.
default&#xa0;
default3.7
default              
defaultThis Code of Practice is a guide to the steps a 
defaultprivate 
defaultkeeper of primates must take to meet the needs of an animal as required by Section 9 of the 
default2006
default Act.  
defaultIt also provides local authority or RSPCA 
defaultinspectors, who may be investigating an allegation of a primate being kept in poor welfare conditions, with guidance on how 
defaultthe primate should be being kept.
default It does not apply to zoos or research establishments (where other guidance is available). 
default&#xa0;
default3.8
default              
defaultTh
defaulte Code of Practice is due to be reviewed in 2015 (five years after it was made).  We will be inviting key stakeholders and experts to take part in the review.
