defaultPet Animals Act 1951
default3.9
default              
defaultThe 1951 Act requires anyone who is in the business of selling animals 
defaultas pets to obtain a valid licence from their local authority.  The local authority has powers to inspect premises and decide whether to issue a licence based on whether the animals will be held in appropriate conditions.  The local authority can issue a li
defaultcence with conditions such as limiting the species of animals the pet shop may sell.
default  The local authority has powers to investigate allegations of cruelty or poor welfare in a pet shop.  The local authority also ha
defaults
default powers to charge a fee to an applicant t
defaulto cover the cost of administering the licensing scheme. 
default&#xa0;
default3.10
default              
defaultAnyone who is in the business of selling animals as pets and does not hold a valid licence 
defaultis 
defaultcommit
defaultting an 
defaultoffence.  The maximum penalty for such an offence is 3 months imprisonment and/or a f
defaultine of £500.
default  
