defaultDangerous Wild Animals Act 1976
default3.11
default              
defaultCertain species of primate deemed sufficiently dangerous are contained in a Schedule to the Dangerous Wild Animals Act 1976 (
defaultthe “1976 Act”
default) and are subject to a licensing regime administered and enforce
defaultd by local authorities. 
default&#xa0;
default3.12
default              
defaultThe precise 
defaultprimate 
defaultspecies listed in the Schedule to the 1976 Act and thereby requiring a licence to keep them are:
default&#xa0;
defaultNew-world monkeys (including: capuchin, howler, 
defaultsaki
default, 
defaultuacari
default, spider and woolly monkeys - night monkeys (also known as owl monkeys) 
defaulttiti
default monkeys and squirrel monkeys are excepted); 
defaultOld-world monkeys (including: baboons, the drill, 
defaultcolobus
default monkeys, the gel
defaultada, guenons, 
defaultlangurs
default, leaf monkeys, macaques, the mandrill, 
defaultmangabeys
default, the 
defaultpatas
default and proboscis monkeys and the 
defaulttalapoin
default); 
defaultAnthropoid apes (chimpanzees, gorillas, 
defaultbonobos
default, and orang-utans);
defaultGibbons and 
defaultSiamangs
default;
defaultLeaping lemurs (including: the indri, and 
defaults
defaultifakas
default - the woolly lemur is excepted); 
defaultLarge lemurs (bamboo or gentle lemurs are excepted).
default&#xa0;
default3.13
default              
defaultThe schedule of listed species was last amended in 2007. The amendments were made in order to reflect species 
defaultbetter 
defaultthat are considered as genuinely danger
defaultous to people – there were criticisms that the previous list was not consistent in this respect.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default3.14
default              
defaultSome 
defaultstakeholders 
defaultwould like to see certain species of primates re-instated on the schedule in order to provide more protection for primates.
default&#xa0;
default However, 
defaultit is important to remember that the 1976 Act is 
defaultprincipally 
defaultabout protecting people from animals rather than providing additional welfare protection to animals.
default&#xa0;
default Therefore the schedule should reflect animals that are considered a genuine threat to the pub
defaultlic.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultSimply to 
defaultplace more species on the schedule as a way of providing an additional regulatory requirement for owners, or potential owners, of primates would 
defaultpotentially 
defaultgo beyond the scope and purpose of the 1976 Act
default and legal advice has confirmed that
default, if species were listed for reasons other than their dangerousness, then there would be a high risk of legal challenge being successful.
default&#xa0;
default3.15
default              
defaultT
defaulthere is no central depository, held either by Defra or DCLG, for information relating to the number of licences
default issued or which species they cover.
default  These are kept within each local authority.
default&#xa0;
default3.16
default              
defaultThe 
default1976 Act
default provides 
defaultsome
default ancillary welfare provisions as a local authority cannot grant a licence unless it is satisfied that the specimens “kept…. under the authorit
defaulty of the licence”: 
default“
defaultbe held in accommodation which secures that the animal will not escape, which is suitable as regards construction, size, temperature, lighting, ventilation, drainage and cleanliness and which is suitable for the number of animals 
defaultproposed to be held in the accommodation, and
default 
defaultbe supplied with adequate and suitable food, drink and bedding material and be visited at suitable intervals
default.”
default&#xa0;
default3.17
default              
defaultThe 
default1976 Act 
defaultis a regulatory piece of legislation rather than a prohibitive one and does not 
defaultdeny the right for people to keep those animals listed on the Schedule as long as an appropriate licence has been obtained.
