default&#xa0;
defaultConvention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES)
default3.18
default              
defaultAll primates are listed on CITES of which the UK is a signa
defaulttory.
default&#xa0;
defaultThrough CITES, the UK works with 178 other countries to protect endangered species of 
defaultanimals 
defaultand 
defaultplants 
defaultby restricting and monitoring international trade in them.  The objective of CITES is not to prohibit all trade in animals and plants, but to ensure that it is carried out in a sustainable way that ensures the long-term survival of all species. 
default CITES proh
defaultibits the commercial importation of the most endangered
default 
defaultAppendix I wild-taken primates in all but exceptional circumstances, such as for breeding or educational purposes which benefit the conservation of the species.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultT
defaultrade in captive-bred specimens is gen
defaulterally considered to be sustainable and so is allowed, subject to certain licensing provisions.
default 
default 
defaultAll imports of primates from outside the EU are subject to strict controls.
default&#xa0;
default3.19
default              
defaultRecords of primates being imported as pets into the UK from outside the EU (n
defaulto CITES records are kept of intra-EU trade) are rare. They 
defaultshow that in the past 5 years (December 2008 – December 2013) only 4 
defaultlive primates have been reported as imported 
defaultfor personal purposes
default 
defaultinto the UK; of these, two were imported by an animal sanctua
defaultry.  
default&#xa0;
default3.20
default              
defaultAlthough CITES is not a welfare Convention, the EU Wildlife Trade Regulations that implement CITES in the EU place a condition on imports of all live Annex A and B species (the EU equivalents of Appendices I and II) that the intended accommodat
defaultion must be adequate to care for the animals properly. This applies to all primates. Such import applications must be accompanied by a detailed description of the intended housing facilities so that the relevant CITES Scientific 
defaultAuthority (the Joint Nature
default Conservation Committee) can assess their adequacy as part of the application.
default&#xa0;
default4.1
default              
defaultDuring 2013, Defra officials asked a representative of private keepers to work with the Pet Advertising Advisory Group (PAAG - a group
default of animal welfare, keeping and veterinary organisations) to draw up guidance and pop-ups
default for internet advertisers (similar to work they have done with other pets).
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default              
defaultPAAG have 
defaultnow 
defaultpublished advice to potential owners of primates which is available on 
defaulttheir website.  Once PAAG know who their affiliated websites will be (those who agree to adopt their minimum standards) those sites will place the pop-ups on their classified pages.   
default&#xa0;
default4.3
default              
defaultWe have been alerted by stakeholders 
defaultthat 
defaultsome 
defaultadvertisements for 
defaultprimates 
defaultmay be 
defaultbogus and an attempt to extract money from unwitting customers in exchange for an animal that doesn’t exist.  The advertisements are allegedly selling a primate in this country but the use of American-English terminology, such as “diaper-tr
defaultained” should arouse suspicion as “diaper” is not in common use in this country.
