default5.1
default              
defaultIt is not clear how many primates are kept privately in this country – the estimates range from 2,500 to 7,500. 
defaultThese are rough estimates base
defaultd around numbers of 1976 
defaultAct 
defaultlicences issued in relation to primates and sales of primates. 
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default              
defaultThe number of pet primates rescued by Monkey World (one of two primate sanctuaries in England) has, according to their records, increased in the last two year
defaults from an average of 0.4 per year from 1989 to 2011, to 15 in 2012 and 11 in 2013.  
defaultWhilst this shows a steep increase it is low
default in absolute terms
default and would be too early to say whether 
defaultsuch figures
default signal a steady rise in primate ownership or a steady rise
default in people alerting the authorities about welfare concerns of primates.
default  We would also need more evidence on which to base any estimates about the numbers of privately held primates.
default&#xa0;
default6.1
default              
defaultSome people have called for 
defaultadditional regulations to help secure the welfare of primates.
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default              
defaultAnimals in zoos are protected not only 
defaultby 
defaultthe Animal Welfare Act 2006 but also 
defaultby 
defaultthe Zoo Licensing Act 1981.  The 1981 Act 
defaultdefines a zoo as an establishment where wild animals (those not 
defaultnormally domesticated in the UK) are kept for exhibition to the public for seven days or more a year.   The Act 
defaultrequires all zoos to have a licence
default, although exemptions from some or all of the provisions of the Act can be allowed for small zoos in specific
default circumstances
default. 
default Zoos are subject to inspection and licensing by their local authority.  
default&#xa0;
default6.3
default              
defaultThere have been calls for individual primate owners to be subject to the same requirements as 
defaultzoos.  Under the 1981 Act, the Secretary of State has published Standards of Modern Zoo Practice with which all zoos are expected to 
defaultcomply 
defaultif they wish to be granted and subsequently retain 
defaulta 
defaultzoo
default licence.   However, the standards go further than requiring
default minimum welfare standards
default for
default the animals.  They also set out how
default zoos should meet the 
defaultconservation 
defaultand education 
defaultrequirements 
defaultof the Act (arising from the EC Zoos Directive), and also how public safety should be secured
default.  Clearly for individual owners th
defaultese requirements will not be required – 
defaultalthough 
defaultfor primates listed in the Schedule to the Dangerous Wild Animals Act 1976 there is a need to prevent injury to people by the animals.  We would therefore not expect to apply 
defaultthe Secretary of State’s Standar
defaultds of Modern Zoo Practice to individual owners.  
defaultHowever, for purposes of animal welfare, w
defaulte consider that the standards set out in the Primate Code of Practice provide primates 
defaultowned by individuals 
defaultwith the same level of protection as those 
defaultkept 
defaultin zoos. 
default In both cases the Animal Welfare Act 2006 would 
defaultapply in the event of any 
defaultcases of cruelty or poor welfare.  
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default7.1
default              
defaultWhilst we agree that people should not be keeping primates in inappropriate conditions th
defaulte available evidence
default does not 
defaultsuggest that th
defaultis 
defaultis a
default 
defaultmajor
default problem.
default  
default&#xa0;
default7.2
default              
defaultWe do not consider that it would be appropriate to seek to ban the keeping of primates as pets because it is already illegal to keep primates in 
default“
defaultpet like conditions
default”,
default i.e. to keep primates in inapprop
defaultriate conditions is an offence under the Animal Welfare Act 2006.  To seek a specific ban on top of the existing law would be difficult to achieve because there would have to be a definition of “pet” or something that differentiates from keeping them in su
defaultitable conditions.  
defaultEven if a definition could be found it is difficult to see what this would achieve that is not currently available under the existing law.
default&#xa0;
default7.3
default              
defaultTo introduce a wider ban on the trade in primates or on all private keeping of primates woul
defaultd mean that 
defaultknowledgeable 
defaultpeople who keep them in appropriate conditions would be unable to continue to do so.  This would penalise law abiding, responsible owners because of the actions of irresponsible owners.  It would be disproportionate and, given the
default number of primates imported as pets (four in last five years), without any 
defaultreal 
defaultfoundation.
default&#xa0;
default7.4
default              
defaultThe Government considers that the existing legislation on the welfare of kept animals and the regulation of the pet trade provide enforcers with appropriate p
defaultowers to take action 
defaultin cases where a primate’s welfare is causing a concern.
default&#xa0;
default7.5
default              
defaultWe also consider that PAAG’s work will help to alert prospective owners of primates 
defaultto 
defaultthe welfare needs 
defaultof 
defaultprimates.  
default&#xa0;
default7.6
default              
defaultThe
default forthcoming
default review of the Primate code of pr
defaultactice will also help to assess whether further action needs to be taken.
